# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qsar-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] The notion of *chemical similarity* (or *molecular similarity*) is one of the most important concepts in cheminformatics.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] These studies are based on the similar property principle of Johnson and Maggiora, which states: *similar compounds have similar properties*.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Chemical similarity is often described as an inverse of a measure of distance in descriptor space.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Examples for inverse distance measures are molecule kernels (graph kernel applied to the description of a molecule as an atom-connectivity graph), that measure the structural similarity of chemical compounds.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] The similarity-based virtual screening (a kind of ligand-based virtual screening) assumes that all compounds in a database that are similar to a query compound have similar biological activity.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Although this hypothesis is not always valid, quite often the set of retrieved compounds is considerably enriched with actives.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] To achieve high efficacy of similarity-based screening of databases containing millions of compounds, molecular structures are usually represented by *molecular screens* (structural keys) or by fixed-size or variable-size *molecular fingerprints*.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Molecular screens and fingerprints can contain both 2D- and 3D-information.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] However, the 2D-fingerprints, which are a kind of binary fragment descriptors, dominate in this area.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Fragment-based structural keys, like MDL keys, are sufficiently good for handling small and medium-sized chemical databases, whereas processing of large databases is performed with fingerprints having much higher information density.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Fragment-based Daylight, BCI, and UNITY 2D (Tripos) fingerprints are the best known examples.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] The most popular similarity measure for comparing chemical structures represented by means of fingerprints is the Tanimoto (or Jaccard) coefficient *T*.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Two structures are usually considered similar if *T* > 0.85 (for Daylight fingerprints).
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] However, it is a common misunderstanding that a similarity of *T* > 0.85 reflects similar bioactivities in general ("the 0.85 myth").
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] The concept of chemical similarity can be expanded to consider chemical similarity network theory, where descriptive network properties and graph theory can be applied to analyze large chemical space, estimate chemical diversity and predict drug target.
[src:qsar-modeling/chemical-similarity] Recently, 3D chemical similarity networks based on 3D ligand conformation have also been developed, which can be used to identify scaffold hopping ligands.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] The rule describes molecular properties important for a drug's pharmacokinetics in the human body, including their absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion ("ADME").
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] However, the rule does not predict if a compound is pharmacologically active.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] The rule is important to keep in mind during drug discovery when a pharmacologically active lead structure is optimized step-wise to increase the activity and selectivity of the compound as well as to ensure drug-like physicochemical properties are maintained as described by Lipinski's rule.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Candidate drugs that conform to the RO5 tend to have lower attrition rates during clinical trials and hence have an increased chance of reaching the market.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Some authors have criticized the rule of five for the implicit assumption that passive diffusion is the only important mechanism for the entry of drugs into cells, ignoring the role of transporters.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Studies have also demonstrated that some natural products break the chemical rules used in Lipinski filters such as macrolides and peptides.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Note that all numbers are multiples of five, which is the origin of the rule's name.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] As with many other rules of thumb, such as Baldwin's rules for ring closure, there are many exceptions.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Veber's Rule further questions a 500 molecular weight cutoff.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] The polar surface area and the number of rotatable bonds has been found to better discriminate between compounds that are orally active and those that are not for a large data set of compounds.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] are predicted to have good oral bioavailability.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] During drug discovery, lipophilicity and molecular weight are often increased in order to improve the affinity and selectivity of the drug candidate.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Hence it is often difficult to maintain drug-likeness (i.e., RO5 compliance) during hit and lead optimization.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Hence it has been proposed that members of screening libraries from which hits are discovered should be biased toward lower molecular weight and lipophilicity so that medicinal chemists will have an easier time in delivering optimized drug development candidates that are also drug-like.
[src:qsar-modeling/lipinski-s-rule-of-five] Hence the rule of five has been extended to the **rule of three** (RO3) for defining **lead-like** compounds.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] The outspread of artificial intelligence and machine learning to computational chemistry has also lead to various attempts to uncover new descriptors or to find the most predictive ones among some sort of candidates.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Invariance to molecular numbering or labeling is assumed as a minimal basic requirement for any descriptor.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Two other important invariance properties, translational invariance and rotational invariance, are the invariance of a descriptor value to any translation or rotation of the molecules in the chosen reference frame.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] These last invariance properties are required for the 3D-descriptors.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] This property refers to the ability of a descriptor to avoid equal values for different molecules.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] In this sense, descriptors can show no degeneracy at all, low, intermediate, or high degeneracy.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] For example, the number of molecule atoms and the molecular weights are high degeneracy descriptors, while, usually, 3D-descriptors show low or no degeneracy at all.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Molecular descriptors are numerical values that encapsulate chemical information about molecules, facilitating their mathematical analysis.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Given the vast array of available descriptors, it's essential to establish foundational principles to ensure their reliability and utility.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Should not be based on experimental properties 9.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] The initial set of principles ensures that a descriptor is well-defined and invariant to manipulations that don't alter the intrinsic molecular structure.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Historically, many descriptors were designed for small organic molecules.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] However, contemporary challenges necessitate descriptors that can be applied to diverse compounds, including salts, ionic liquids, peptides, polymers, and nanostructures.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] The subsequent set of guidelines emphasizes the descriptor's practical utility.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] An effective descriptor should be interpretable, correlate with experimental properties, and provide unique information not captured by other descriptors.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Continuity and low degeneracy are crucial, as they ensure the descriptor can sensitively reflect minor structural variations.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Ultimately, the information a descriptor provides is contingent upon the chosen molecular representation and its alignment with the specific property or activity being studied.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Here there is a list of a selection of commercial and free descriptor calculation tools.
[src:qsar-modeling/molecular-descriptor] Official version discontinued (last update 2019), but has a community-maintained fork.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In the physical sciences, a **partition coefficient** (***P***) or **distribution coefficient** (***D***) is the ratio of concentrations of a compound in a mixture of two immiscible solvents at equilibrium.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] This ratio is therefore a comparison of the solubilities of the solute in these two liquids.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The partition coefficient generally refers to the concentration ratio of un-ionized species of compound, whereas the distribution coefficient refers to the concentration ratio of all species of the compound (ionized plus un-ionized).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In the chemical and pharmaceutical sciences, both phases usually are solvents.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Most commonly, one of the solvents is water, while the second is hydrophobic, such as 1-octanol.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hence the partition coefficient measures how hydrophilic ("water-loving") or hydrophobic ("water-fearing") a chemical substance is.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Partition coefficients are useful in estimating the distribution of drugs within the body.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hydrophobic drugs with high octanol-water partition coefficients are mainly distributed to hydrophobic areas such as lipid bilayers of cells.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Conversely, hydrophilic drugs (low octanol/water partition coefficients) are found primarily in aqueous regions such as blood serum.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] If one of the solvents is a gas and the other a liquid, a gas/liquid partition coefficient can be determined.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] For example, the blood/gas partition coefficient of a general anesthetic measures how easily the anesthetic passes from gas to blood.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Partition coefficients can also be defined when one of the phases is solid, for instance, when one phase is a molten metal and the second is a solid metal, or when both phases are solids.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The partitioning of a substance into a solid results in a solid solution.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Partition coefficients can be measured experimentally in various ways (by shake-flask, HPLC, etc.) or estimated by calculation based on a variety of methods (fragment-based, atom-based, etc.).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] If a substance is present as several chemical species in the partition system due to association or dissociation, each species is assigned its own *K*ow value.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] A related value, D, does not distinguish between different species, only indicating the concentration ratio of the substance between the two phases.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Despite formal recommendation to the contrary, the term *partition coefficient* remains the predominantly used term in the scientific literature.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In contrast, the IUPAC recommends that the title term no longer be used, rather, that it be replaced with more specific terms.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] where *K*D is the process equilibrium constant, [A] represents the concentration of solute A being tested, and "org" and "aq" refer to the organic and aqueous phases respectively.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The IUPAC further recommends "partition ratio" for cases where transfer activity coefficients can be determined, and "distribution ratio" for the ratio of total analytical concentrations of a solute between phases, regardless of chemical form.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The **partition coefficient**, abbreviated ***P***, is defined as a particular ratio of the concentrations of a solute between the two solvents (a biphase of liquid phases), specifically for un-ionized solutes, and the logarithm of the ratio is thus **log *P***.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] When one of the solvents is water and the other is a non-polar solvent, then the log *P* value is a measure of lipophilicity or hydrophobicity.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] To a first approximation, the non-polar phase in such experiments is usually dominated by the un-ionized form of the solute, which is electrically neutral, though this may not be true for the aqueous phase.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] *M* is used to indicate the number of ionized forms; for the I-th form (*I* = 1, 2, ... , *M*) the logarithm of the corresponding partition coefficient, $\log P_{\text{oct/wat}}^{I}$ , is defined in the same manner as for the un-ionized form.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] To distinguish between this and the standard, un-ionized, partition coefficient, the un-ionized is often assigned the symbol **log *P*0**, such that the indexed $\log P_{\text{oct/wat}}^{I}$ expression for ionized solutes becomes simply an extension of this, into the range of values *I* > 0.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] For measurements of distribution coefficients, the pH of the aqueous phase is buffered to a specific value such that the pH is not significantly perturbed by the introduction of the compound.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In the above formula, the superscripts "ionized" each indicate the sum of concentrations of all ionized species in their respective phases.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In addition, since log *D* is pH-dependent, the pH at which the log *D* was measured must be specified.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In areas such as drug discovery—areas involving partition phenomena in biological systems such as the human body—the log *D* at the physiologic pH = 7.4 is of particular interest.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] It is often convenient to express the log *D* in terms of *P*I, defined above (which includes *P*0 as state *I* = 0), thus covering both un-ionized and ionized species.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] which sums the individual partition coefficients (not their logarithms), and where $f^{I}$ indicates the pH-dependent mole fraction of the I-th form (of the solute) in the aqueous phase, and other variables are defined as previously.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The values for the octanol-water system in the following table are from the Dortmund Data Bank.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] They are sorted by the partition coefficient, smallest to largest (acetamide being hydrophilic, and 2,2',4,4',5-pentachlorobiphenyl lipophilic), and are presented with the temperature at which they were measured (which impacts the values).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Values for other compounds may be found in a variety of available reviews and monographs.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Critical discussions of the challenges of measurement of log *P* and related computation of its estimated values (see below) appear in several reviews.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] A drug's distribution coefficient strongly affects how easily the drug can reach its intended target in the body, how strong an effect it will have once it reaches its target, and how long it will remain in the body in an active form.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hence, the log *P* of a molecule is one criterion used in decision-making by medicinal chemists in pre-clinical drug discovery, for example, in the assessment of druglikeness of drug candidates.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Likewise, it is used to calculate lipophilic efficiency in evaluating the quality of research compounds, where the efficiency for a compound is defined as its potency, via measured values of pIC50 or pEC50, minus its value of log *P*.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In the context of pharmacokinetics (how the body absorbs, metabolizes, and excretes a drug), the distribution coefficient has a strong influence on ADME properties of the drug.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hence the hydrophobicity of a compound (as measured by its distribution coefficient) is a major determinant of how drug-like it is.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] More specifically, for a drug to be orally absorbed, it normally must first pass through lipid bilayers in the intestinal epithelium (a process known as transcellular transport).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] For efficient transport, the drug must be hydrophobic enough to partition into the lipid bilayer, but not so hydrophobic, that once it is in the bilayer, it will not partition out again.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Likewise, hydrophobicity plays a major role in determining where drugs are distributed within the body after absorption and, as a consequence, in how rapidly they are metabolized and excreted.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In the context of pharmacodynamics (how the drug affects the body), the hydrophobic effect is the major driving force for the binding of drugs to their receptor targets.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] On the other hand, hydrophobic drugs tend to be more toxic because they, in general, are retained longer, have a wider distribution within the body (e.g., intracellular), are somewhat less selective in their binding to proteins, and finally are often extensively metabolized.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In some cases the metabolites may be chemically reactive.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hence it is advisable to make the drug as hydrophilic as possible while it still retains adequate binding affinity to the therapeutic protein target.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The hydrophobicity of a compound can give scientists an indication of how easily a compound might be taken up in groundwater to pollute waterways, and its toxicity to animals and aquatic life.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Partition coefficient can also be used to predict the mobility of radionuclides in groundwater.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In the field of hydrogeology, the octanol–water partition coefficient *K*ow is used to predict and model the migration of dissolved hydrophobic organic compounds in soil and groundwater.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hydrophobic insecticides and herbicides tend to be more active.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hydrophobic agrochemicals in general have longer half-lives and therefore display increased risk of adverse environmental impact.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In metallurgy, the partition coefficient is an important factor in determining how different impurities are distributed between molten and solidified metal.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] It is a critical parameter for purification using zone melting, and determines how effectively an impurity can be removed using directional solidification, described by the Scheil equation.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Many other industries take into account distribution coefficients, for example in the formulation of make-up, topical ointments, dyes, hair colors and many other consumer products.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] A number of methods of measuring distribution coefficients have been developed, including the shake-flask, separating funnel method, reverse-phase HPLC, and pH-metric techniques.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In this method the solid particles present into the two immiscible liquids can be easily separated by suspending those solid particles directly into these immiscible or somewhat miscible liquids.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The classical and most reliable method of log *P* determination is the *shake-flask method*, which consists of dissolving some of the solute in question in a volume of octanol and water, then measuring the concentration of the solute in each solvent.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The most common method of measuring the distribution of the solute is by UV/VIS spectroscopy.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] A faster method of log *P* determination makes use of high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The log *P* of a solute can be determined by correlating its retention time with similar compounds with known log *P* values.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] An advantage of this method is that it is fast (5–20 minutes per sample).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The pH-metric set of techniques determine lipophilicity pH profiles directly from a single acid-base titration in a two-phase water–organic-solvent system.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hence, a single experiment can be used to measure the logarithms of the partition coefficient (log *P*) giving the distribution of molecules that are primarily neutral in charge, as well as the distribution coefficient (log *D*) of all forms of the molecule over a pH range, e.g., between 2 and 12.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The method does, however, require the separate determination of the pKa value(s) of the substance.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Polarized liquid interfaces have been used to examine the thermodynamics and kinetics of the transfer of charged species from one phase to another.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The first is ITIES, "interfaces between two immiscible electrolyte solutions".
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Here a reaction at a triple interface between a conductive solid, droplets of a redox active liquid phase and an electrolyte solution have been used to determine the energy required to transfer a charged species across the interface.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] There are attempts to provide partition coefficients for drugs at a single-cell level.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] This strategy requires methods for the determination of concentrations in individual cells, i.e., with Fluorescence correlation spectroscopy or quantitative Image analysis.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Partition coefficient at a single-cell level provides information on cellular uptake mechanism.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] There are many situations where prediction of partition coefficients prior to experimental measurement is useful.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] For example, tens of thousands of industrially manufactured chemicals are in common use, but only a small fraction have undergone rigorous toxicological evaluation.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Hence there is a need to prioritize the remainder for testing.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] QSAR equations, which in turn are based on calculated partition coefficients, can be used to provide toxicity estimates.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Calculated partition coefficients are also widely used in drug discovery to optimize screening libraries and to predict druglikeness of designed drug candidates before they are synthesized.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] As discussed in more detail below, estimates of partition coefficients can be made using a variety of methods, including fragment-based, atom-based, and knowledge-based that rely solely on knowledge of the structure of the chemical.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Other prediction methods rely on other experimental measurements such as solubility.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The methods also differ in accuracy and whether they can be applied to all molecules, or only ones similar to molecules already studied.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Standard approaches of this type, using atomic contributions, have been named by those formulating them with a prefix letter: AlogP, XlogP, MlogP, etc.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] A conventional method for predicting log *P* through this type of method is to parameterize the distribution coefficient contributions of various atoms to the overall molecular partition coefficient, which produces a parametric model.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] This parametric model can be estimated using constrained least-squares estimation, using a training set of compounds with experimentally measured partition coefficients.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In order to get reasonable correlations, the most common elements contained in drugs (hydrogen, carbon, oxygen, sulfur, nitrogen, and halogens) are divided into several different atom types depending on the environment of the atom within the molecule.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] While this method is generally the least accurate, the advantage is that it is the most general, being able to provide at least a rough estimate for a wide variety of molecules.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The most common of these uses a group contribution method and is termed cLogP.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] It has been shown that the log *P* of a compound can be determined by the sum of its non-overlapping molecular fragments (defined as one or more atoms covalently bound to each other within the molecule).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Fragmentary log *P* values have been determined in a statistical method analogous to the atomic methods (least-squares fitting to a training set).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] In addition, Hammett-type corrections are included to account of electronic and steric effects.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] A typical data-mining-based prediction uses support-vector machines, decision trees, or neural networks.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] This method is usually very successful for calculating log *P* values when used with compounds that have similar chemical structures and known log *P* values.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Molecule mining approaches apply a similarity-matrix-based prediction or an automatic fragmentation scheme into molecular substructures.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Furthermore, there exist also approaches using maximum common subgraph searches or molecule kernels.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] For prediction of p*K*a, which in turn can be used to estimate log *D*, Hammett type equations have frequently been applied.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] There are a variety of approaches to predict solubilities, and so log *S*.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The partition coefficient between *n*-Octanol and water is known as the ***n*-octanol-water partition coefficient**, or *K*ow.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] It is also frequently referred to by the symbol P, especially in the English literature.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] It is also known as ***n*-octanol-water partition ratio**.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Values for log *K*ow typically range between -3 (very hydrophilic) and +10 (extremely lipophilic/hydrophobic).
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] The values listed here are sorted by the partition coefficient.
[src:qsar-modeling/partition-coefficient] Acetamide is hydrophilic, and 2,2′,4,4′,5-Pentachlorobiphenyl is lipophilic.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] In QSAR modeling, the predictors consist of physico-chemical properties or theoretical molecular descriptors of chemicals; the QSAR response-variable could be a biological activity of the chemicals.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] QSAR models first summarize a supposed relationship between chemical structures and biological activity in a data-set of chemicals.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Second, QSAR models predict the activities of new chemicals.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Related terms include **quantitative structure–property relationships** (QSPR) when a chemical property is modeled as the response variable.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] "Different properties or behaviors of chemical molecules have been investigated in the field of QSPR.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] As an example, biological activity can be expressed quantitatively as the concentration of a substance required to give a certain biological response.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Additionally, when physicochemical properties or structures are expressed by numbers, one can find a mathematical relationship, or quantitative structure-activity relationship, between the two.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The mathematical expression, if carefully validated, can then be used to predict the modeled response of other chemical structures.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The error includes model error (bias) and observational variability, that is, the variability in observations even on a correct model.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The basic assumption for all molecule-based hypotheses is that similar molecules have similar activities.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] This principle is also called Structure–Activity Relationship (SAR).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The underlying problem is therefore how to define a *small* difference on a molecular level, since each kind of activity, e.g. reaction ability, biotransformation ability, solubility, target activity, and so on, might depend on another difference.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Examples were given in the bioisosterism reviews by Patanie/LaVoie and Brown.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] In general, one is more interested in finding strong trends.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Created hypotheses usually rely on a finite number of chemicals, so care must be taken to avoid overfitting: the generation of hypotheses that fit training data very closely but perform poorly when applied to new data.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The *SAR paradox* refers to the fact that it is not the case that all similar molecules have similar activities.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Analogously, the "partition coefficient"—a measurement of differential solubility and itself a component of QSAR predictions—can be predicted either by atomic methods (known as "XLogP" or "ALogP") or by chemical fragment methods (known as "CLogP" and other variations).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] It has been shown that the logP of compound can be determined by the sum of its fragments; fragment-based methods are generally accepted as better predictors than atomic-based methods.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Fragmentary values have been determined statistically, based on empirical data for known logP values.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] This method gives mixed results and is generally not trusted to have accuracy of more than ±0.1 units.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Group or fragment-based QSAR is also known as GQSAR.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] GQSAR allows flexibility to study various molecular fragments of interest in relation to the variation in biological response.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The molecular fragments could be substituents at various substitution sites in congeneric set of molecules or could be on the basis of pre-defined chemical rules in case of non-congeneric sets.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] GQSAR also considers cross-terms fragment descriptors, which could be helpful in identification of key fragment interactions in determining variation of activity.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Lead discovery using fragnomics is an emerging paradigm.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] In this context FB-QSAR proves to be a promising strategy for fragment library design and in fragment-to-lead identification endeavours.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] An advanced approach on fragment or group-based QSAR based on the concept of pharmacophore-similarity is developed.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] This method, pharmacophore-similarity-based QSAR (PS-QSAR) uses topological pharmacophoric descriptors to develop QSAR models.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] This activity prediction may assist the contribution of certain pharmacophore features encoded by respective fragments toward activity improvement and/or detrimental effects.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The acronym **3D-QSAR** or **3-D QSAR** refers to the application of force field calculations requiring three-dimensional structures of a given set of small molecules with known activities (training set).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The training set needs to be superimposed (aligned) by either experimental data (e.g. based on ligand-protein crystallography) or molecule superimposition software.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] It uses computed potentials, e.g. the Lennard-Jones potential, rather than experimental constants and is concerned with the overall molecule rather than a single substituent.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The first 3-D QSAR was named Comparative Molecular Field Analysis (CoMFA) by Cramer et al.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] It examined the steric fields (shape of the molecule) and the electrostatic fields which were correlated by means of partial least squares regression (PLS).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The created data space is then usually reduced by a following feature extraction (see also dimensionality reduction).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The following learning method can be any of the already mentioned machine learning methods, e.g. support vector machines.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] An alternative approach uses multiple-instance learning by encoding molecules as sets of data instances, each of which represents a possible molecular conformation.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] A label or response is assigned to each set corresponding to the activity of the molecule, which is assumed to be determined by at least one instance in the set (i.e. some conformation of the molecule).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] On June 18, 2011 the Comparative Molecular Field Analysis (CoMFA) patent has dropped any restriction on the use of GRID and partial least-squares (PLS) technologies.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] In this approach, descriptors quantifying various electronic, geometric, or steric properties of a molecule are computed and used to develop a QSAR.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] This approach is different from the fragment (or group contribution) approach in that the descriptors are computed for the system as whole rather than from the properties of individual fragments.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] This approach is different from the 3D-QSAR approach in that the descriptors are computed from scalar quantities (e.g., energies, geometric parameters) rather than from 3D fields.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] An example of this approach is the QSARs developed for olefin polymerization by half sandwich compounds.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] It has been shown that activity prediction is even possible based purely on the SMILES string.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Similarly to string-based methods, the molecular graph can directly be used as input for QSAR models, but usually yield inferior performance compared to descriptor-based QSAR models.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] QSAR has been merged with the similarity-based read-across technique to develop a new field of q-RASAR.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The DTC Laboratory at Jadavpur University has developed this hybrid method and the details are available at their laboratory page.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Recently, the q-RASAR framework has been improved by its integration with the ARKA descriptors in QSAR.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] In the literature it can be often found that chemists have a preference for partial least squares (PLS) methods, since it applies the feature extraction and induction in one step.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Computer SAR models typically calculate a relatively large number of features.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Because those lack structural interpretation ability, the preprocessing steps face a feature selection problem (i.e., which structural features should be interpreted to determine the structure-activity relationship).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Feature selection can be accomplished by visual inspection (qualitative selection by a human); by data mining; or by molecule mining.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] A typical data mining based prediction uses e.g. support vector machines, decision trees, artificial neural networks for inducing a predictive learning model.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Molecule mining approaches, a special case of structured data mining approaches, apply a similarity matrix based prediction or an automatic fragmentation scheme into molecular substructures.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Furthermore, there exist also approaches using maximum common subgraph searches or graph kernels.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Typically QSAR models derived from non linear machine learning is seen as a "black box", which fails to guide medicinal chemists.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Recently there is a relatively new concept of matched molecular pair analysis or prediction driven MMPA which is coupled with QSAR model in order to identify activity cliffs.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] QSARs are being applied in many disciplines, for example: risk assessment, toxicity prediction, and regulatory decisions in addition to drug discovery and lead optimization.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Obtaining a good quality QSAR model depends on many factors, such as the quality of input data, the choice of descriptors and statistical methods for modeling and for validation.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Any QSAR modeling should ultimately lead to statistically robust and predictive models capable of making accurate and reliable predictions of the modeled response of new compounds.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] 4. data randomization or Y-scrambling for verifying the absence of chance correlation between the response and the modeling descriptors.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The success of any QSAR model depends on accuracy of the input data, selection of appropriate descriptors and statistical tools, and most importantly validation of the developed model.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Validation is the process by which the reliability and relevance of a procedure are established for a specific purpose; for QSAR models validation must be mainly for robustness, prediction performances and applicability domain (AD) of the models.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Some validation methodologies can be problematic.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] For example, *leave one-out* cross-validation generally leads to an overestimation of predictive capacity.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Even with external validation, it is difficult to determine whether the selection of training and test sets was manipulated to maximize the predictive capacity of the model being published.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Different aspects of validation of QSAR models that need attention include methods of selection of training set compounds, setting training set size and impact of variable selection for training set models for determining the quality of prediction.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Development of novel validation parameters for judging quality of QSAR models is also important.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] One of the first historical QSPR applications (as pre-condition to QSAR) was to predict boiling points.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] It is well known for instance that within a particular family of chemical compounds, especially of organic chemistry, that there are strong correlations between structure and observed properties.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] A simple example is the relationship between the number of carbons in alkanes and their boiling points.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] There is a clear trend in the increase of boiling point with an increase in the number carbons, and this serves as a means for predicting the boiling points of higher alkanes.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] A still very interesting application is the Hammett equation, Taft equation and pKa prediction methods.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The biological activity of molecules is usually measured in assays to establish the level of inhibition of particular signal transduction or metabolic pathways.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Drug discovery often involves the use of QSAR to identify chemical structures that could have good inhibitory effects on specific targets and have low toxicity (non-specific activity).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Of special interest is the prediction of partition coefficient log *P*, which is an important measure used in identifying "druglikeness" according to Lipinski's Rule of Five.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] While many quantitative structure activity relationship analyses involve the interactions of a family of molecules with an enzyme or receptor binding site, QSAR can also be used to study the interactions between the structural domains of proteins.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Protein-protein interactions can be quantitatively analyzed for structural variations resulted from site-directed mutagenesis.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] It is part of the machine learning method to reduce the risk for a SAR paradox, especially taking into account that only a finite amount of data is available (see also MVUE).
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] In general, all QSAR problems can be divided into coding and learning.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] (Q)SAR models have been used for risk management.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] QSARS are suggested by regulatory authorities; in the European Union, QSARs are suggested by the REACH regulation, where "REACH" abbreviates "Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals".
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Regulatory application of QSAR methods includes *in silico* toxicological assessment of genotoxic impurities.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Commonly used QSAR assessment software such as DEREK or CASE Ultra (MultiCASE) is used to genotoxicity of impurity according to ICH M7.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The chemical descriptor space whose convex hull is generated by a particular training set of chemicals is called the training set's applicability domain.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] Prediction of properties of novel chemicals that are located outside the applicability domain uses extrapolation, and so is less reliable (on average) than prediction within the applicability domain.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The assessment of the reliability of QSAR predictions remains a research topic, as a unified strategy has yet to be adopted by modellers and regulatory authorities.
[src:qsar-modeling/qsar] The QSAR equations can be used to predict biological activities of newer molecules before their synthesis.
